Let's think step by step. When the volume and surface area of a sphere are numerically equal, it means that:

\begin{align*}
\dfrac{4}{3} \pi r^3 &= 4 \pi r^2 \\[2ex] \dfrac{r^3}{3} &= r^2 \\[2ex] \dfrac{r^2}{3} &= r^2 - r^3 \\[2ex] -\dfrac{r^3}{3} &= r^2 - r^3 \\[2ex] -\dfrac{r^2}{3} &= r^2(1-\dfrac{1}{3}) \\[2ex] \dfrac{-1}{3} &= 1-\dfrac{1}{3} \\[2ex] \dfrac{1}{3} &= 0 \\[2ex] False
\end{align*}

This contradiction shows that the volume and surface area of a sphere cannot be numerically equal. Therefore, the answer is: There is no such sphere.
